nodes.bodyText: Just noting that this looks like a small method and should get inlined, but it is not a guarantee. @cathyzhyi should we consider adding this to the always worth inlining list?
opened an issue for adding the method to the list #8831
@fjeremic Does this helper method treat the third parameter as unsigned? If not, there's potential for overflow here because in Java 8, strings can be longer than Integer.MAX_VALUE / 2 characters.

I just took a look at the Z implementation for this intrinsic and only parts of it treat the value as unsigned. Other parts treat it as signed. As such yeah there is definitely a bug here today. Can we add a length check to ensure the third parameter is non-negative?
I think we need to fix the intrinsic, otherwise we would effectively reduce the maximum string length by half.

I think we need to fix the intrinsic, otherwise we would effectively reduce the maximum string length by half.

Or we can just not call the intrinsic for this extreme case, which is what I was suggesting. To fix the intrinsic we would have to do it across all platforms which exploit it which could take time and resources just to handle an extreme case.
I hadn't thought of that: I'll make that change.
Need to double check returning the identical string is appropriate here.

The API docs [1] don't say anything special about that case.
[1] https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#replace-
java.lang.CharSequence-java.lang.CharSequence-
Testing on the RI shows a copy is returned, OpenJ9 should have the same behavior for compatibility even though it's not specified or likely to cause any problem.
